name: Visualization & Digital Design Poster Session at Rice OEDK
description:
Join us for a student poster session at the Oshman Engineering Design Kitchen (OEDK).

The posters come out of a Digital Design and Visualization course where students learn visual communication using Computer Aided Design, the Adobe Creative Suite, and through the reconstruction of medical imaging data (CT, MRI, etc.).

Student posters will tell the story of a human body part (or a vegetable (!)) that experiences some sort of trauma (think Phineas Gage). This trauma will be displayed via the reconstruction of medical imaging data. Then, a regenerative scaffold that fits the defect will be placed into the defect. This regenerative scaffold will be tailored to the geometry and anatomical site. Students will stand by their poster able to answer questions about their work or process.

Feel free to stop by anytime between 2pm and 5pm and stay for as little or long as you like.

Directions to the OEDK

The OEDK is located immediately off of Entrance 21 on Rice Blvd. on Rice's campus. When you arrive, park in the parking lot across from the building and then walk over to the OEDK. The front door will be unlocked and you may walk in at any point and mingle. Hope you can make it to see some incredible student work. 


Problems or questions? Contact Matthew Wettergreen, mwettergreen@rice.edu, 713-825-4613

name: March Meetup ⚡ Lightning Data Visualization Server + well,  Lightning Talks
description:
conversation + networking to 7p

THEN lightning talks + an introduction to the open-source Lightning Data Visualization Server from neuroscientist and visualization researcher @thefreemanlab 

⚡ Lightning is a data-visualization server providing API-based access to reproducible, web-based, interactive visualizations. It includes a core set of visualization types, but is built for extendability and customization. Lightning supports modern libraries like d3.js and three.js, and is designed for interactivity over large data sets and continuously updating data streams.


http://lightning-viz.org/

name: Chiasm for linked d3js charts + Lightning Talks  // August Meetup
description:
conversation to 7p

lightning talks 


⚡ Greg Smith - Using leaflet.js and mapbox for map data

 THEN

@currankelleher on the visualization platform Chiasm

Curran maintains the Chiasm open-source project and creates interactive data visualizations with d3js at Alpine Data Labs.

Chiasm is a browser based runtime environment and plugin architecture for interactive visualizations. It allows plugins for data access, data transformation, and interactive visualization to be loaded and configured dynamically.

Projects like Chiasm aim to abstract away some of the more difficult-to-implement 'wiring' necessary to create linked interactive d3js visualizations like this.

 https://github.com/curran/chiasm/

name: XVSY - grammar of graphics based data exploration in clojure // September Meetup
description:
conversation to 7p,

⚡ lightning talks

Ju will share his work on a network diagram to understand the relationship between local venues and HIV risk in Houston

 then

Dave will be talking about XVSY, a toy project for grammar of graphics based data exploration implemented in Clojure. The goal of XVSY was to learn about data visualization via maximal re-invention. Thus, XVSY has no dependencies on libraries like d3.js, ggplot2, etc. This talk will feature an architectural overview and then a brief visual analysis of Medicare Part D prescription data to fact-check claims made in this New York Times article regarding prescribing patterns for the treatment of macular degeneration. 

See more from Dave here: http://davetsao.com/

name: Tableau as a “rapid prototyping” tool // October Meetup
description:
conversation to 7p 

then ⚡ lightning talks 


Clay will share an interactive map dashboard made in Microsoft's Power BI

speaker to follow

Aaron will be presenting two talks:


1. How to use Tableau as a “rapid prototyping” tool. Aaron has been using Tableau for more than 7 years and will share a workflow that may be useful even to those of us who choose another environment.

2. The art & science of data visualization. He'll briefly cover a range of topics like graphical excellence, honesty in data visualization, telling effective stories,  Gestalt laws of perceptual organization, how the visual perception system works, Bertin’s retinal properties, Cleveland & McGill’s graphical perception properties. If there's interest, we'll have more discussion about these topics in the future.


To follow along with the tutorial, you'll want to have your own copy of Tableau. Here are the download links for Tableau Public (free to use forever, but you can only save to your Tableau Public profile on the web):

In our most recent data jam, people worked to visualize a modestly sized (~200k tweets) Twitter dataset. We saw a wide range of tools employed to test interesting ideas.

This Month, we'll have a round of lightning presentations and discussion about those ideas, the process used, what the results were, and what we can learn from them.

Then, Wanjun will demonstrate how easy it is to get started with Plotly - a service for hosting your plots on the web. She'll show us a cool project using Plotly with the Raspberry Pi.

And Amin will show us a tool called Circos, a software package for visualizing data in a circular layout. He'll explain to us how to get started, and how he uses it in his work.

Ju will present Graphical inference

'The human understanding, on account of its own nature, readily supposes a greater order and uniformity in things than it finds. And ... it devises parallels and correspondences and relations which are not there.' 

-- Francis Bacon, 1620

Is what we see really there? How can we avoid tricking ourselves into seeing patterns where there are none.
